But based on what was said in the conversation, he did choose the destruction of the human race, and so did the others.  As the transcipt shows, by entering the source, he would again have to choose 13 survivors to rebuild Zion (which completely makes no sense given the timeline of the movie, unless we assume they are much, much further in the future than 2199), the code would reset and the cycle would repeat.  Rather, he chooses to enter the matrix and save Trinity. Now, if we are to assume the &quot;Neo's&quot; on the screens behind him are the previous 4 incarnations of the one, they all make the same choice and head to the door on his left, leading to the matrix, and as the Architect says, the destruction of the human race.(At least I remember his previous selves heading in the same direction.  If they didn't, ignore the rest of the argument.)  <br>
<br>
So, are we to assume that the doors were switched this time, explaining why the other's headed to the same door?  Or rather they also chose to reenter the matrix, the entire human race that was attached to the matrix died in a cataclysmic system crash and the bots had to start from scratch growing new ones?  Or rather, the architect is full of crap <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     (Or the brother's overlooked this, and it will be corrected in the DVD release).  Personally, I think there's some truth to the 3rd.  <br>
<br>
The architect wasn't expecting Neo, and was hoping he'd be wiped out prior to his arrival.  However, against all odds, he wasn't, and the architect now has to bluff Neo into NOT entering the source or the machines are toast.  How to do this?  Manipulate the system to give him a choice he can't make...sacrificing Trinity, and bluffing by saying to enter the source is to allow the machines to continue enslaving the humans.  Contrary to the thoughts in the essay, the machines do know humans are unpredictable, driven more by their emotions, and count on him choosing Trinity over the source.  By manipulating Neo, the architect has him choose not to enter the source, and prevents Neo from winning at this point.  Personally, I believe if he had entered the source, it would have been game over for the machines and there wouldn't have been a 3rd movie.<br>
<br>
The other thing that drives me to this conclusion is this:  If the machines know 1% won't accept the program, and it's pretty easy for them to tell which don't (they wake up and are subsequently flushed), why allow this at all.  What point is there in allowing them to escape?  If those that don't accept upset the program from within, just get rid of them.  Machine logic should be able to figure this one out.  When they detect one that's not accepting the program: Eliminate, reduce, recycle.  In the first matrix, as soon as Neo wakes a robot moves into detach him, why not just squish him then and there?  The argument that the machines' programing doesn't allow it is hogwash, as clearly they have no problem killing humans throughout the rest of the 1st and 2nd movie. (of course, this also means there wouldn't be a movie at all, so there needs to be a few truck sized plot holes in the movies...)<br>
<br>
So, either there's a few major inconistencies that need to be cleared up either in the DVD, or explained in the 3rd movie, or the Architect is bluffing throughout the entire scene, and Neo (Being Keanu after all...) falls for it, hook, line and sinker. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jaelyndimathe>Jaelyn DiMathe</A> at: 5/22/03 10:53:07 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kurley>Kurley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 769<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/22/03 10:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1566.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Yeeeeaah ...  8^p</span><hr size=1> &quot;The other thing that drives me to this conclusion is this: If the machines know 1% won't accept the program, and it's pretty easy for them to tell which don't (they wake up and are subsequently flushed), why allow this at all.&quot;<br>
<br>
Two theories:<br>
<br>
1 - presuming that Zion is still within the Matrix (i.e. not really real), then the whole One Prophecy and Zion are just another form of control to catch that percentage of the population that rejects the &quot;1999 Matrix&quot;.  While the Architect cannot control who or when rejects the program, they can exercise control over where those people go.  So rather than having these &quot;rebels&quot; going this way and that, they all funnel into yet another program of control.<br>
<br>
2 - presuming that Zion is in fact the real world, then again the aim is to funnel those who reject the &quot;1999 Matrix&quot; into an area where they can be contained and dealt with.<br>
<br>
Personally, I have a difficult time with the concept that a real Zion has been destroyed and rebuilt 5 times - there are too many flaws with that concept (technology development, population growth, etc...) within the rough timeframe presented.  I suppose if the machines secretly aided in the restructuring of Zion, that might explain it, but it seems a little far fetched - even for the Matrix.<br>
<br>
I don't think that Zion being within the Matrix is unreasonable, but that presents the problem of &quot;where does it end?&quot;.<br>
<br>
When you get down to it, you'll find holes with any storyline like this because it presents the fantastic (i.e. based on our understanding of science and energy, humans would serve as LOUSY power sources, but it makes a cool story) so sometimes you just gotta go with it.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jaelyndimathe>Jaelyn DiMathe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Guardian of Truth</span><br>  Posts: 495<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/22/03 11:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1566.topic&index=38>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://myweb.cableone.net/agunders/jae.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Yeeeeaah ...  8^p</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>1 - presuming that Zion is still within the Matrix (i.e. not really real), then the whole One Prophecy and Zion are just another form of control to catch that percentage of the population that rejects the &quot;1999 Matrix&quot;. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
